in Your IntelliJ IDEA Environment 

During our work as developers, we often use a certain library to help us reduce our boilerplate code etc. But in most cases, once the dependency is added to the pom, it stays there forever. In this article, you will find out why this can cause vulnerabilities in our system and meet a powerful tool that can help you write better and more secure software.

 
 
 
 
 

Google Announces Cloud Code: Extending IntelliJ and Visual Studio Code to Kubernetes Apps 

Recently Google introduced a new developer tool called Cloud Code. With Cloud Code, developers will get a set of plugins for development environments like JetBrains IntelliJ Idea IDE and Microsofts Visual Studio Code. Check the article to see how this tool can help you accelerate the development lifecycle of your applications in the cloud!

 
 
 
 
 
 

There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 
 

A New Era for Determining Equivalence in Java? 

Taking inspiration from libraries like Lombok, the Java community is pushing for updating the Java language, trying to reduce the verbosity. 
The paper “Equivalence” by Liam Miller-Cushon, April 2019 proposes to create a library solution to help produce readable, correct, and performant implementations of equals() and hashCode().

 
 
 
 
 

How to Generate
Source Code? 

Do you think generating source code whenever possible is the best option for your code? This post by our colleague Peter Verhas tries to evaluate whether you should write all the code you can manually. It also covers the different phases of software development where the source code can be generated programmatically and compares the different approaches. Check it out!

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Google Releases New Java Logging Framework 

Google recently announced the release of a new open-source Java logging framework called Flogger. Acknowledging that "[t]he field of open-source Java logging APIs is already extremely crowded", Google asserts that Flogger offers "many benefits over existing logging APIs". These improvements include reducing the cost of disabled log statements, increasing overall readability, and allowing extensibility.

 
 
 
 

Heterogeneous Comparisons 

Mixing Comparable and inheritance can be very dangerous, especially if you are not aware of the guidelines how to implement compareTo() method. Read the article to find out more about this pitfall.

 
 
 
 
 

Consistency Through Compensation in Microservices 

Consistency is a common challenge when designing distributed systems. Take a look at one approach by which you can achieve resiliency in your application even under server crashes and any intermediate failures.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

A beginner’s guide to Hibernate Statistics 

Hibernate provides a very powerful Statistics mechanism that, unfortunately, is lesser known.
While it is not enabled by default, you will see that many applications can benefit from using it, especially when it comes to determining cache effectiveness.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

The Future of Spring Cloud Microservices After Netflix Era 

When it comes to Spring Cloud, it is mostly associated with Netlix stack. It is quite surprising that Pivotal has announced that most of Spring Cloud Netflix modules are entering maintenance mode.
This is a great article explaining all the details about migration strategies and the existing alternatives of the Netflix modules.

 
 
 
 
 

Add Secure Token Authentication to Your Java App 

JSON Web Tokens are the standard for securing modern web applications. Used properly, they address a range of security concerns, including cross-site scripting attacks (XSS), man-in-the-middle attacks (MITM), and cross-site request forgery (CSRF). They also give us the benefit of inspectable metadata and strong cryptographic signatures. In this post, you'll take a deep dive into JWTs beginning with how they work, and then digging into how to configure a Spring Boot app with Okta to use JWT authentication.

 
 
 
 

Exploring Dependency Override in Spring 

Sometimes you may end up with the need of overriding dependencies defined among multiple Spring contexts. In this post, you will examine different options to do that, how to analyse the whole dependency graph for a bean and automatically export the definition of the dependent ones to the child context. The objective is to be able to reduce the amount of code you write when overriding beans in child contexts. Check it out!

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Vertx in Production 

Vert.x is an incredibly performant framework to implement low latency services. Its multi-reactor pattern makes it possible to process many requests per second in a few milliseconds. In this article, you will get the lessons of operating production services based on this library with the help of many examples.

 
 
 
 

Cold Flows, Hot Channels 

See how you can utilise Kotlin coroutines as primitives for cold and hot data streams how Kotlin Flows, cold asynchronous streams, build on top of coroutines.
In the second part of the article, Simple design of Kotlin Flow, you will peek under the hood, examine their design, and see how a combination of language features and a library enables a powerful abstraction with simple design.

A good craftsman knows their tools. Being a software developer is no exception. So, while programming and to stay in the flow of coding, it might be worthwhile to know some keyboard shortcuts and to not be distracted by clicking on menu items. This blogpost is focused on IntelliJ and it summarises the most important tools, so be sure to check it out!
